he custom class compiled with Scala 2.13 and how bytecode calls might refer to interface defaults. The catch here is that at runtime with Scala 2.11, there are no default methods available. This makes me wonder if I really need to create a custom setup to handle this or if there’s a way to work around it, given the version discrepancies. It’s a bit of a conundrum, but I’ll keep exploring the options!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_sUntfFtHePUT9SRAjWLSPcbv|fc_09fc4ef5ab1d38ce016a255fd63a648197af59b08dc8954cd0", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "javap -classpath /home/vjovanov/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.scala-lang/scala-library/2.13.16/9e064d9304904fd7b6bd2b55a9e601b8c1c9006e/scala-library-2.13.16.jar scala.reflect.ClassTag | grep newArray -A2 -B2"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2051, "output": 1419, "cacheRead": 39424, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 42894, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780834233358, "responseId": "resp_09fc4ef5ab1d38ce016a255fb9e8408197b9f1e2b26f1afdfc"}}
